„Éª„Éª„Éª
‚ÄúFourteen years ago, Billy raised his right hand and swore an oath to protect life and property in the City of New York. He achieved his lifelong dream of becoming a New York City Firefighter. He did it with heart, determination and unwavering commitment. Billy swore to always be ready to answer the call for help and he did just that day and night, responding from his firehouse on Myrtle Avenue, and always going towards the danger to save others‚Ä¶never away. He had a true passion for being a Firefighter. This job was a part of him,‚Äù said #FDNY Commissioner Daniel A. Nigro at today‚Äôs funeral for FDNY Firefighter William N. Tolley. ‚ÄúBilly was a young man with a big smile, and an even bigger heart ‚Äì one filled with immense love for his family, his many aunts, uncles and cousins, and especially his young daughter Isabella. His love of being a Firefighter, and a musician, they paled in comparison to the love for his little girl. Bella, being your father made him proud, and brought him a joy that fighting a fire could never replicate.‚Äù View the full funeral service at http://bit.ly/FDNYTolley (URL is case-sensitive)

content:
Ask yourself, would you like to be the recipient if your life was on the line?  Then sign up and be willing to #bethematch it takes only a couple seconds, it does not hurt to swab and you won't die if you are asked to give stem cells or bone marrow, yet others we love cannot live without it. #Repost @fdny
"We owe him everything. It's hard to put into words how it feels," says Dawn Traynor, mother of 14-year old Kyle Richardson, who was diagnosed with Hodgkin‚Äôs Lymphoma in 2015, and who received a bone marrow transplant in March, 2016, using cells donated by FDNY Firefighter Robert Humphries. Today, Kyle and Firefighter Humphries met for the first time, at the 13th annual Honor Roll of Life ceremony held at #FDNY Headquarters in Brooklyn. Firefighter Humphries says, ‚ÄúThere was no hesitation. I would have done it no matter who it was. It‚Äôs a good feeling knowing that you can help.‚Äù To learn how you can make a difference in someone‚Äôs life, follow @NewYorkBloodCenter and visit www.bethematch.org
